#VintageOfTheDay: Sometimes I can’t help but keep pieces from my shop for myself. Like this recent early 90s Rena Rowan navy blue find.

Rena Rowan was actually one of the co-founders of the Jones Apparel group, but was never credited as such. She was also married to Vic Damone, who was famous for the 1956 hit song, “On the Street Where You Live.”

A little fashion history for you on this Wednesday.

#VintageOfTheDay - Today it’s all about vintage jewelry. I’ve been wearing these two vintage charm bracelets that belonged to my Mom. One has three charms representing my two sisters and me with our names and birthdates. The other is a gift my Dad gave to my Mom when they were dating in the 1950s. It’s a silver heart with her name on one side and his on the other. Wearing these makes me feel closer to both of them, since the older I get, the more I miss them. ❤️
#VintageOfTheDay: This is actually an H&M faux-suede trench coat that I’m wearing as a dress, but the boots are vintage 90s Steve Madden and they have a cool gold trim on the block heel. 👢

There’s a reason for these flowers…and this smile.
 
For the last few months, I’ve been struggling with debilitating depression, triggered by my rescue cat Pickles being diagnosed with cancer. Pickles lost so much weight. It reminded me of when my Mom stopped eating shortly before she died. I would beg and plead with Mom to eat something. It was so painful watching her waste away. I thought if I could just get her to eat, she’d get better and live forever. I know nobody lives forever. But that doesn’t stop you from wanting them to. I felt like I didn’t take good enough care of my mom. And now I felt like I hadn’t taken good enough care of Pickles.
 
My depression got to the point that now I wasn’t eating. All I wanted to do was sit on the couch and cry. I hid my depression from everyone because I was so ashamed of the way I felt. Then it got to a very dark place. I actually thought about taking a handful of sleeping pills and getting into my swimming pool. I just didn’t want to feel the pain anymore.
 
That’s when I knew I needed help. I immediately made an appointment to speak with a mental health professional. That phone call saved my life. I started taking an anti-depressant. I started regular sessions with a therapist. I told my friends and family what I was going through. And the support and understanding I received helped me realize I wasn’t alone in my struggles. 
 
On Sunday night, we had to make the difficult decision to let Pickles go. She died peacefully in our arms at the emergency animal clinic. I cried so hard and my eyes were so swollen that my iPhone didn’t even recognize my face scan. If I didn’t have the medicine and the tools I’ve been learning in my therapy sessions, I don’t know if I would have been able to mentally handle the trauma. But I did. And I’m so grateful.
 
This beautiful bouquet was sent to me yesterday by my best friend Missy. I can’t look at these flowers and not smile. I know I have a lot to be thankful for. I’m well on the road to recovering from depression. And that’s certainly something to smile about. 
 
If you’re suffering from depression, please talk to someone. I promise you…it does get better.

There’s a beautiful story behind this beautiful 1960s brown nightgown. I had a photo of my Mom wearing a similar gown on Christmas morning when I was very young. (See last photo.) She looked so glamorous and I always wanted to find this vintage piece to add to my personal collection.

I searched for years and finally found an exact match on Etsy. The gown was in perfect condition when I received it, so I went to leave the seller a great review and saw that she lived in Anniston, Alabama, which is a short drive Gadsden, from the town I grew up in.

I included the photo of my Mom and me from that Christmas Eve and sent her a note to tell her I was from Gadsden. She messaged me back and said the bought this gown at a thrift store in Gadsden. We both realized this gown could have actually been my Mom’s. ❤️
